                <td bgcolor="#0A0634" valign="top"><font color="#FFFFFF" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;04/30/2003&nbsp;: 03:03:06 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> The game has evolved to the point wherein that exists a LARGE gap between the high-end players and more casual, mid-way or low-end players.  There is simply very little direct comparisons that can be made anymore.  Vtyn, I think, made this rather clear with his comments.<br /><br />Focus items are a great idea for the lower-end players who often run into problems with going oom while exping, not killing fast enough, and/or wanting to do a bit more damage in groups/raids.  This is typically not true of the higher-end necros who are far more concerned with being able to survive AE's or a round of melee by an elemental mob.<br /><br />Now given the above, I'm going to go off on a tangent and say this:<br /><br />Focus effects on items dropped in the elemental planes really don't add up.<br /><br />I mean, honestly, how many effects in elemental PoP are genuinely better than the focus effects you can obtain in VT? <br /><br />How many of those effects really give as much of an increase as, say, Ifir does for a rogue?<br /><br />How many of those effects really justify giving up a better stat wise item for?<br /><br />Frankly, the problem with focus items not being used as much in the higher-end game is more than just that the higher-end game is different.<br /><br />It's also because the higher-end focus effects really aren't very impressive.<br /><br />Add a focus effect that increases crit rate or one that increases DD damage ALWAYS by 20%, and then you'll see them appear more in people's magelos.  Add a focus effect that helps penetrate mob resistances, and that item would become one of the most highly sought in the game.<br /><br />The item has to match up with the kind of players that are able to obtain that particular item.  This goes for any form of content, really.<br /></span></font></td>
